{
  "texts": [
    "In hyperbolic space, there are at least two such parallel lines.",
    "This change comes with many consequences and as a result, hyperbolic geometry can be seen as a geometry of constant negative curvature.",
    "In the context of deep learning this geometry has many attractive properties, such as its hierarchical structure and exponential expansion.",
    "Empowered by these geometric properties, hierarchical embeddings have in recent years been performed in hyperbolic space with great success (Nickel & Kiela, 2017), leading to unparalleled abilities to embed deep and complex trees with minimal distortion (Ganea et al., 2018a; Sala et al., 2018; Sonthalia & Gilbert, 2020; Verbeek & Suri, 2014; Chami et al., 2020a).",
    "This has led to rapid advances in hyperbolic deep learning across many disciplines and research areas, including but not limited to graph networks (Chami et al., 2019; Liu et al., 2019; Dai et al., 2021; Sarkar, 2011; Sun et al., 2021a; Yang et al., 2022a; Wang et al., 2023b), text embeddings (Tifrea et al., 2019; Zhu et al., 2020; Dhingra et al., 2018; Dai et al., 2020), molecular representation learning (Klimovskaia et al., 2020; Yu et al., 2020; Wu et al., 2021; Qu & Zou, 2022b), and recommender systems (Mirvakhabova et al., 2020; Wang et al., 2021; Yang et al., 2022b; Li et al., 2022; Vinh Tran et al., 2020; Chamberlain et al., 2019; Vinh et al., 2018)."
  ]
}